      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are absolutely right to worry about \"random glitches,\" because in the world of automotive mechanics, those are often the most frustrating parts of the job. The alternator, battery, and wiring are the big three, but there are many smaller, sneaky culprits that cause exactly the kind of intermittent behavior you described.\n\nOne of the most common suspects is the **starter solenoid**. This is the heavy-duty switch that actually engages the engine to turn the car over. If its internal contacts are worn out or corroded, it can sometimes work perfectly fine when you first turn the key, but then suddenly fail to engage, causing the lights to flicker or the engine to stall. It's like a faulty faucet that works when you push it, but then suddenly stops letting water flow.\n\nAnother classic culprit is the **alternator diode**. These are tiny electronic components inside the alternator that allow current to flow in one direction only. If one of these diodes fails, it can cause the alternator to stop charging the battery while the engine is running, leading to those weird voltage drops and lights dimming. It's like a one-way valve that suddenly breaks and lets water back out, causing the pressure to drop.",
